Assosciation Rule Mining COVID 19

Gaurav

7/3/2020

COVID-19 open research data challenge (CORF-19) aims to find out what we know about COVID-19 risk factors. Specifically, this challenge wants to know if literature is available on different risk factors and if so, what does literature report about it? Traditionally machine learning has two main areas: descriptive and predictive analysis. Descriptive focuses on explaining things in the past and present such as what, why, when, how, etc. This objective of descriptive aligns with our problem statement, so we choose descriptive modeling. The data provided for this task is unlabeled. Association rule discovery is an unsupervised data mining technique that finds out the meaningful and unknown relationships between different features. We want to know the association and correlation between different risk factors and COVID-19, so the purpose and assumptions behind association rule mining concur with our objective. This competition was hosted by Kaggle (An AI challenge with AI2, CZI, MSR, Georgetown, NIH & The White House)

Data Preprocessing and Preparation

Unlike traditional flat-file data, the data given to us is abstract and titles of the research papers. So, it is essential to preprocess and clean this data and convert it into a standard flat file. For converting text data into the flat file we used a bag-of-words model using tm and qdap package. A bag-of- words is a representation of text that describes the occurrence of words within a document. We cleaned the data by using standard techniques such as removing stop words, punctuations, reducing the sparseness, etc. to reduce the size of the data in a horizontal direction.

library(qdap)
library(tm)

library(tidyverse)

data = read.csv("metadata.csv")

#Preprocessing the Titles
title.text <- data$title

#corpus
title.text.source <- VectorSource(title.text)
title.corpus <- VCorpus(title.text.source)

#cleaning
title.corpus <- tm_map(title.corpus, stripWhitespace)
title.corpus <- tm_map(title.corpus, removePunctuation)
title.corpus <- tm_map(title.corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
title.corpus <- tm_map(title.corpus, removeWords, stopwords("en"))
#title.corpus <- tm_map(title.corpus, stemDocument)

title.dtm <- DocumentTermMatrix(title.corpus)

#Reducing Sparsness
title.dtm.less.sparse <- removeSparseTerms(title.dtm, 0.95)
title.matrix <- as.matrix(title.dtm.less.sparse)

To make sure the keywords related to risk factors should be included in the data we created a risk dictionary so that these keywords will not be lost in cleaning.
Risk Dictionary- Smoking, smoke, pregnancy, pregnant, coinfections, comorbidities, morbidities, social, socioeconomic, economic, sars, mers, covid19 Similary we preprocessed the abstract data

To further reduce the size of the data and include relevant documents in the analysis we created the 3 class labels CoronaRisk, which includes information about coronaviruses and risks associated with it another class is coronavirus, which just indicates the article is about coronavirus and third class of Anonymous. So here we assume that if certain keywords related to coronavirus risk are present along with the word coronavirus word in either title or abstract we assume that that document is about coronavirus risk factors. We just included data points related to CoronaRisk in our dataset because we are interested in coronavirus risk factors.

#Creating Class lables
library(dplyr)
db_new <- db %>% 
  mutate(class = ifelse((coronavirus_t>0 | coronavirus>0| covid19>0)  & 
                          (smoking>0 | smoke >0 |coinfections>0 |
                             comorbidities>0 |morbidities>0|natal>0|
                             socioeconomic>0|pregnancy>0|pregnant>0|social>0|
                             economic>0|sars>0|mers>0|susceptibility>0), "coronaRisk", 
                        ifelse((coronavirus_t==0 & coronavirus==0 & covid19==0) ,  "anonymous", "coronavirus")))
db_new$class=as.factor(db_new$class)
summary(db_new$class)
##   anonymous  coronaRisk coronavirus

To further clean the data we removed deamplification words, adverbs, action verbs, preposition etc.

#Further data cleaning
db_new=db_new[!names(db_new)%in% c(deamplification.words,action.verbs,adverb,
                                   BuckleySaltonSWL, preposition,"study",'however',
                                   'furthermore')
              ]
db=db[!names(db)%in% c(deamplification.words,action.verbs,adverb,
                       BuckleySaltonSWL, preposition,"study",'however',
                       'furthermore')
      ]

#Only include coronaRisk class to reduce the dimension of the data
db_new=subset(db_new, class=="coronaRisk")
write.csv(db_new,'data_clean.csv')

Rule Mining

covid = read.csv("data_clean.csv")
covid= covid[,-c(1,2,3,4,173)]

#Converting the word frequencies to True and False
#Removing unwanted vaiables 
numeric_cols <- vapply(covid, is.numeric, logical(1))
covid[numeric_cols] <- as.factor(as.character(covid[numeric_cols] != 0))
covid=covid[,-168]
covid[1:167]=lapply(covid[1:167], factor)
covid$journal<-NULL

Another difficult part of this project is determining what minimum support, lift and confidence would be used for the trimming down of important rules. With how sparse the database is (1965 instances and 166 variables with False being majority value), support is left as the last determinant for the rule mining, and we first looked at lift and confidence.

#looking for rules with risk factors in the title of the journal
#More rules can be mined by chnaging the items in rhs by different key words related to corona risks
rules <- apriori(covid, 
                 parameter=list(support =0.002, confidence =0.0, minlen=3, maxlen=10), 
                 appearance = list(rhs=c( "social=TRUE","economic=TRUE","socioeconomic=TRUE"), default="lhs"))

Mined Rules

The first larger item set was a 6-item set including the words respiratory, covid-19, coronavirus, sars, mers and pregnancy. Obviously, the first 5 are constructed to be in the left hand side, while pregnancy was the supposed effect on the right hand side. This suggested that someone who is pregnant might be at greater risk in contracting or being severely affected by the coronavirus such as SARS, MERS or COVID19. Below is documentation of all five 5-item sets meeting minimum lift to create a 6-item set.

The second larger item set that was created involved smoking as the right hand side variable. By again creating rules that had a lift value greater than 1, a 4-item set rule was created showing the connection between coronavirus, respiratory, covid-19 and smoking. It shows us that a person having weak respiratory is at higher risk of getting infected by coronavirus and COVID-19

The above table shows some of the interesting rules for the social and economic factors. These rules indicate that we know about social risks such as social, socioeconomic and economic factors that are linked to COVID-19 and coronaviruses. The rules suggest that we have research on mortality rates, epidemic, responses and strategies to mitigate pandemics such as COVID-19. The keywords production and understanding implies that we have a better understanding of the economic impact of coronavirus than COVID-19 which is true because COVID-19 is a recent pandemic.

The table shows us that respiratory diseases and the presence of infections and comorbidities are related to COVID-19. It may imply that patients with these conditions may be at higher risks. But as COVID-19 is new, these rules are again accompanied by some key words such as observed, detected, potential which conveys the insufficient data and ambiguity in the research field regarding this.

In above table, the key words in the LHS have words like pathogens, multiple, collected, factors, mechanism and assay which shows that we know more things about coronavirus than COVID-19; because these words are indicators that we know something for sure. But in the case of COVID-19, we dont have those strong indicators.

Conclusion

The rules found in this project can be used to further understand COVID-19 and its association with different risk factors. Using this dataset and mining the association rules, it can be implied that patients or people with conditions such as pregnancy, weak respiratory due to smoking or other diseases are at higher risk of getting infected. In the case of COVID-19 and the coronavirus, research has been published which discusses the strategies, responses to epidemics and effects of epidemic on the society and economy. In the case of COVID-19, usually, patients with coinfections, influenza and comorbidities are at higher risks but in case of coronavirus it is confirmed that they are at higher risks. Other less frequent or rules with poor lift and support were ignored. To sum it up, COVID-19 being a novel disease, we have a very limited knowledge about the risk factors associated with the same.
